===Etymology===
From {{inh|en|enm|paleys}}, from {{der|en|fro|palais}}, which comes from {{der|en|la|palātium}}, from {{m|la|Palātium}}, in reference to the [[Palatine]] ({{w|Palatine Hill}}), one of the seven hills of Rome, where the aristocracy of the Roman [[republic|Republic]]—and later, Roman emperors—built large, splendid residences<ref>{{w|Palatine#Derivative_terms}}</ref><ref>https://www.oxford-royale.co.uk/articles/14-fascinating-word-origins-english-language.html</ref>. The name is ultimately either from {{der|en|ett|-}}, the same source as {{m|la|Pales||{{w|Pales}}, the Italic goddess of shepherds, flocks and livestock}}, or Latin {{m|la|palus||stake; enclosure}}. {{doublet|en|palazzo|Pfalz}}.

